          "body": "Genesis 31 does not begin with Jacob deciding to leave — it begins with God commanding him to leave (31:3). The distinction is crucial for interpretation. Jacob's departure is not a refugee's escape improvised from fear; it is obedience to a specific divine mandate grounded in a specific covenant history ('I am the God of Bethel,' 31:13). The reference to Bethel is deliberate: twenty-two years earlier (Genesis 28:10-22) Jacob had vowed to return if God kept him safe and prosperous. God now calls in that vow. The command is simultaneously an act of grace (the promise 'I will be with you,' 31:3) and an act of covenant accountability (the reminder of the vow, 31:13). Jacob is not merely being released from servitude; he is being summoned to covenant fidelity. Every subsequent action in the chapter — the consultation with Rachel and Leah, the flight, the confrontation with Laban, the covenant at Gilead — takes place under this originating divine word."
