        "excerpt": "God came to Laban the Aramean in a dream of the night and said to him, 'Be careful that you do not speak to Jacob either good or bad.'",
        "body": "The departure scene (31:17-21) is narrated with deliberate irony. Jacob has received a divine command; his exit nevertheless looks nothing like obedient homecoming. He 'deceived Laban the Aramean by not telling him that he was fleeing' (31:20) — the narrator uses the Hebrew *ganav* ('stole'), the same root applied to Rachel's theft of the teraphim (31:19). The verbal link is intentional: Jacob steals Laban's daughters the same way Rachel steals Laban's gods. The family shares a common disposition toward concealment. Jacob's own explanation in 31:31 — 'I was afraid, for I thought that you would take your daughters from me by force' — is not an implausible fear, but it is a faith failure: the God who commanded the return and promised presence (31:3) was capable of managing the departure without deception.\n\nThe pursuit is equally significant. Laban takes his kinsmen and pursues seven days (31:23) — a formidable armed response, as 31:29 makes clear: 'It is in my power to do you harm.' This is not bluster. Laban commands sufficient force to reclaim his daughters and property by violence. The entire outcome of the chapter hangs on one verse: 31:24. God appears to Laban in a nocturnal dream with a single restraining command — 'Be careful that you do not speak to Jacob either good or bad.' The phrase 'good or bad' is a Hebrew merism for 'anything at all' — total restraint of Laban's agency. The man who arrives at Gilead with the power to harm (31:29) has already been disarmed by God before the confrontation begins.\n\nThe theological argument is precise: Jacob's safety is not secured by his head start across the Euphrates, nor by his cunning in departing secretly. It is secured by divine preemptive action in the mind of his pursuer. Calvin observed on this verse that God often uses the dreams and fears of the ungodly as instruments of His protective purpose — Laban is not a believer, yet he obeys the divine restraint. Spurgeon extended this: 'The LORD can bridle the most malicious of enemies by working on them within.' The chapter insists that the covenant patriarch's protection is a matter of divine governance, not human resourcefulness.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ganav lev* ('stole the heart,' 31:20) is an idiom for deception by concealment — literally to steal someone's judgment or perception. The NASB renders it 'deceived,' capturing the sense. The same root three times in 31:19-27 creates a verbal web linking Rachel's theft, Jacob's deception, and Laban's accusation — the narrator refuses to exempt any party from the indictment."
