        "excerpt": "If the God of my father, the God of Abraham, and the Fear of Isaac, had not been for me, surely now you would have sent me away empty-handed. God has seen my affliction and the toil of my hands, so He rendered judgment last night.",
        "body": "The confrontation between Laban and Jacob (31:26-42) is structured as a formal legal proceeding. Laban makes three accusations: unauthorized departure with his daughters (31:26-27), denial of farewell rites (31:28), and theft of his gods (31:30). Jacob's response addresses each in reverse order — he handles the gods accusation first (31:31-32), then issues a counter-challenge calling for a public search (31:36-37), and finally delivers his comprehensive defense of twenty years of service (31:38-42). The rhetorical structure is that of a *riv* — a legal complaint procedure well attested in the Hebrew prophets (cf. Micah 6:1-8; Isaiah 1:18) where parties present their cases before witnesses.\n\nJacob's defense in 31:38-41 is striking for its specificity. He enumerates: no miscarried ewes or goats (meaning his shepherding was not negligent), no consumption of the flocks' rams, personal financial liability for torn animals (the law of Exodus 22:10-13 later codifies the shepherd's responsibility), sleepless vigilance in extreme weather, fourteen years of labor for wives, six years for flocks, and ten wage-changes. The catalog is not emotional — it is evidentiary. Jacob is presenting the record of a man who kept faith with his employer even when the employer was systematically defrauding him.\n\nThe climax is 31:42. Jacob does not conclude with 'therefore I am right' — he concludes with 'therefore God has seen and judged.' The theological argument runs: the reason I am not arriving empty-handed after twenty years of wage-cheating is not that I outsmarted Laban; it is that God observed what Laban was doing to me and intervened. The divine name 'the Fear of Isaac' at this crucial moment is not incidental — it evokes the quality of God that makes Him both a reliable witness (He sees everything, 31:42a) and a reliable judge (He acts on what He sees, 31:42b). Douglas Stuart has noted that this is one of the clearest Old Testament statements of retributive justice operating within ordinary economic relationships — God does not reserve His justice for the spectacular; He renders it 'last night' in the dispute between a cheated herdsman and his fraudulent employer.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Yakhach* ('rendered judgment,' 31:42; same root in 31:37 'decide between us') is a legal term for arbitration or rebuke — the arbiter who pronounces a verdict. Its appearance in both Jacob's appeal for a human tribunal (31:37) and his claim of divine verdict (31:42) creates a deliberate parallel: Jacob asked for human witnesses; God provided divine adjudication instead. *Oni* ('affliction,' 31:42) is the same word used of Israel's bondage in Egypt (Exodus 3:7) — Jacob's suffering under Laban foreshadows the nation's suffering under Pharaoh, and God's response ('He rendered judgment') prefigures the Exodus."
